ce:section.ce:para:
C-dots are becoming excellent choice as fluorescence probes for the detection of biologically and environmentally relevant metal ions [10,12,14,31]. This increased surge in their applicability is owing to their highly beneficial properties such as photo stability, low toxicity, water dispersibility and biocompatibility. In this study, fluorescence property of synthesize C-dots was investigated in the presence of various metal ions and the relative change in intensity is shown in Fig. 3
                        (i). No major quenching of fluorescence was observed with most of the metal ions except Fe3+, Co2+ and Ni2+ which caused some reduction whereas Cu2+ and Hg2+ caused very strong fluorescence quenching of C-dots. It is postulated that the presence of oxygen containing groups (OH, C = O, COOH) present on the surface of C-dots can interact with metal ions (especially Cu2+ and Hg2+) causing the C-dots to behave as chelating agents [46]. Generally, the quenching is observed due to electron or energy transfer between the excited C-dots and metal ions. In this case, the quenching phenomena is due to the electron transfer and not via energy transfer, because there is no overlap between the absorption spectrum of Cu2+/Hg2+ and PL emission spectrum of C-dots (Fig. S4) [22]. Moreover, fluorescence lifetime decay was calculated for C-dots in absence and presence Cu2+ and Hg2+ ions. The average lifetime of C-dots was calculated to be 7.61 ns which decreased to 6.02 and 4.09 ns upon adding Cu2+ and Hg2+ respectively (Fig. 3vi). This result indicates that the electron transfer from excited C-dots to vacant orbital of metal ions leads to the strong non radiative electron/hole recombination confirming aggregation-induced emission quenching in Cdots-M2+ (Scheme 2
                        ). When a strong chelator of Cu2+ and Hg2+, EDTA was added to the solution, metal ions were removed from the surface of C-dots due to the formation of respective M2+-EDTA complexes and the fluorescence of C-dots was restored (Figs. S5 and S6).
